"Prasada Rao D.G.V., Khan M.A.Q.","Zebra mussels: Enhancement of copper toxicity by high temperature and its relationship with respiration and metabolism",2000,"Water Environment Research","72","2",,"175","178",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0034078120&partnerID=40&md5=76b695b687c2bc09827489dd27229b56",,"Prasada Rao, D.G.V.; Khan, M.A.Q.","Increase in water temperature from an ambient of 15 °C to 20 and 25 °C increased the respiration rate in zebra mussels, Dreissena polymorpha, by 50 and 175%, respectively, and increased the toxicity of copper; a 48-hour lethal concentration to kill 50% of the organisms (LC50) of 775 μg/L at 20 °C decreased to 238 μg/L at 25 °C, and a 96-hour LC50 of 487 μg/L at 20 °C reduced to 107 μg/L at 25 °C. The oxygen consumption rate in the presence of 150 μg/L copper decreased by 16% at 20 °C and by 50% at 25 °C. Thus, high temperatures may increase the toxicity of copper, and possibly other metals, to zebra mussels. Similar increases in heavy metal toxicity may also accompany global warming, which is expected to raise surface water temperature by 2 to 3 °C. Such temperature and heavy metal combinations may also be useful in designing field trials to control this nuisance species.","Heavy metal toxicity; Metabolism; Respiration; Temperature; Zebra mussels","Copper toxicity; Copper; Ecosystems; Global warming; Metabolism; Oxygen; Toxicity; Water pollution; copper; animal experiment; animal tissue; article; controlled study; high temperature; metabolic regulation; mussel; nonhuman; pest control; priority journal; toxicity testing; Animalia; Dreissena polymorpha; Invertebrata",,"copper, 15158-11-9, 7440-50-8",,,,"Abbott, W.S., A method of computing the effectiveness of an insecticide (1925) J. Econ. Entomol., 18, p. 263; Balaji, M., Toxicity of copper to the fouling bivalve Mytilopsis sallei (1989) Abstr. Workshop Mar. Wood Biodeterioration, , Ind. Acad. Sci., Waltair, India; Cairns, J.J., Bahus, T.K., Burton, D.T., Dickson, K.L., Sparks, R.E., Walter, W.T., The effect of pH, solubility and temperature upon the acute toxicity of zinc to the Bluegill sunfish Leopmis macrochirus (1971) RAF Trans. Kans. Acad. Sci., 74, p. 81; Cairns J., Jr., Heath, A.G., Parker, B.C., The effects of temperature upon the toxicity of chemicals to aquatic organisms (1975) Hydrobiologia, 47, p. 135; Callow, M.E., A review of biofouling in fresh waters (1993) Biofouling, 7, p. 313; Chung, K.S., Lethal effects of cadmium, chromium, copper and zinc in Nerita fulgurans (1978) Biol. Inst. Oceanogr., 17 (1-2), p. 31; Davenport, J., Redpath, K.J., Copper and the mussel Mytilus edulis toxins (1984) Drugs and Pollutants in Marine Animals, , L. Bolis, J. Zadunaisky, and R. Gilles (Eds.), Springer-Verlag, Berlin Heidelberg, Ger; Depledge, H.M., Enhanced copper toxicity resulting from environmental stress factors synergies (1987) Comp. Biochem. Physiol., 87 C (1), p. 15; Finney, D.J., (1971) Probit Analysis. 3rd Ed., , Cambridge University Press, New York; Ganapati, P.N., Rao, D.G.V.P., Studies on the respiration of barnacles: Oxygen uptake and metabolic rate in relation to body size in Balanus amphoursite communis (Darwin) (1960) J. Anim. Physiol., 7, p. 27; Hung, Y.-W., Effects of temperature and chelating agents on cadmium uptake in the American oyster (1982) Bull. Environ. Contam. Toxicol., 28, p. 546; Klerks, P.L., Fraleigh, C.P., Uptake of nickel and zinc by zebra mussels Dresissana polymorpha (1997) Arch. Environ. Contam. Toxicol., 32, p. 191; Kraak, M.H.S., Lavy, D., Toussaint, H., Wilma, H., Peeters, M., Davids, C., Toxicity of the heavy metals to zebra mussels (Dreissena polymorpha) (1993) Zebra Mussels, Biology, Impacts and Control, p. 491. , T.F. Nalepa and D.W. Schloesser (Eds.), Lewis Publishers, Boca Raton, Fla; Kraak, M.H.S., Lavy, D., Schon, H., Toussiant, M., Wilma, H., Peeters, M., Staalen, N.V., Ecocotoxicity of mixtures of metals to zebra mussel (Dreissena polymorpha) (1994) Environ. Toxicol. C